To compute the derivative of the function \( f(x) = 3x^3 - 2x^2 + x - 5 \), we can use the power rule for differentiation. The power rule states that if \( f(x) = ax^n \), then \( f'(x) = n \cdot ax^{n-1} \).\n\nApplying this rule to each term in the function:\n\n1. For \( 3x^3 \): \n   \[\n   \frac{d}{dx}(3x^3) = 3 \cdot 3x^{3-1} = 9x^2\n   \]\n\n2. For \( -2x^2 \): \n   \[\n   \frac{d}{dx}(-2x^2) = -2 \cdot 2x^{2-1} = -4x\n   \]\n\n3. For \( x \): \n   \[\n   \frac{d}{dx}(x) = 1\n   \]\n\n4. For the constant \( -5 \): \n   \[\n   \frac{d}{dx}(-5) = 0\n   \]\n\nNow, combining all these results, we get the derivative:\n\n\[\nf'(x) = 9x^2 - 4x + 1\n\]\n\nThus, the derivative of the function \( f(x) \) is:\n\n\[\nf'(x) = 9x^2 - 4x + 1\n\]\n